    &nbsp;The material-browser is an interface between the material-database on disk, and the user’s  scene. Its main adoption has been in maya, but it is made to be easily adapted to other applications supporting Qt (described in the code-overview below).
  </p>

  <p>
    Before the interface, the users had no easy way of importing materials into their scene without using an external application. Initially the material browser was only intended to import materials, but throughout development it also became the defacto tool for managing materials within the scene, and on objects (the scene- and selection tab).
  </p>

  <p>
    Making this interface was my first introduction to Qt and UI programming, and over the various iterations the browser went through, I learned a lot about the various quirks and features of Qt, and how to maintain large python applications.&nbsp;<br>
